        <h4>Toxicological Mechanisms</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hyperthermia:</strong> Loss of sweating ability leads to dangerous overheating</li>
          <li><strong>Cardiac toxicity:</strong> Tachycardia progressing to arrhythmias and cardiac arrest</li>
          <li><strong>Respiratory depression:</strong> Central and peripheral effects on breathing</li>
          <li><strong>Seizures:</strong> CNS excitation at high doses</li>
          <li><strong>Dehydration:</strong> Loss of saliva production and sweating</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Historical Medical Applications</h4>
        <p>Before synthetic alternatives, belladonna was used medically for motion sickness (scopolamine patches still used), eye dilation during exams, antispasmodic effects, and as a surgical anesthetic. However, the narrow therapeutic window made it extremely dangerous, leading to its replacement by safer synthetic anticholinergics.</p>
